qas.question: Along with Poland and Hungary, what Eastern European state grew in power?
During what century did Portugal devote itself to overseas expansion?
What nation lost the Hundred Years' War?
What was the regnal name of Henry Tudor?
Along with Denmark and Sweden, what country was part of the Union of Kalmar?

context: In modern-day Germany, the Holy Roman Empire continued to rule, but the elective nature of the imperial crown meant there was no enduring dynasty around which a strong state could form. Further east, the kingdoms of Poland, Hungary, and <a0_0>Bohemia<a0_0/> grew powerful. In Iberia, the Christian kingdoms continued to gain land from the Muslim kingdoms of the peninsula; Portugal concentrated on expanding overseas during the <a1_0>15th<a1_0/> century, while the other kingdoms were riven by difficulties over royal succession and other concerns. After losing the Hundred Years' War, <a2_0>England<a2_0/> went on to suffer a long civil war known as the Wars of the Roses, which lasted into the 1490s and only ended when Henry Tudor (r. 1485–1509 as <a3_0>Henry VII<a3_0/>) became king and consolidated power with his victory over Richard III (r. 1483–85) at Bosworth in 1485. In Scandinavia, Margaret I of Denmark (r. in Denmark 1387–1412) consolidated <a4_0>Norway<a4_0/>, Denmark, and Sweden in the Union of Kalmar, which continued until 1523. The major power around the Baltic Sea was the Hanseatic League, a commercial confederation of city states that traded from Western Europe to Russia. Scotland emerged from English domination under Robert the Bruce (r. 1306–29), who secured papal recognition of his kingship in 1328.
